---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'FLSA Overtime Rules Explained | wagetheftcalc.com';
const description = 'A plain-English guide to FLSA overtime requirements, the 40-hour threshold, and common exemptions.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>FLSA Overtime Rules Explained</h1>
  <h2>The Basic Rule</h2>
  <p>Non-exempt employees must receive 1.5× their regular rate of pay for all hours worked over 40 in a single workweek. "Workweek" is a fixed recurring 168-hour period — employers set the start day.</p>
  <h2>Who Is Exempt?</h2>
  <p>The FLSA's "white collar" exemptions cover bona fide executive, administrative, and professional employees who are paid on a salary basis of at least $684/week (the 2024 threshold; litigation ongoing regarding 2024 DOL rule increases). Job title alone does not create an exemption — the actual job duties must meet specific criteria.</p>
  <h2>Regular Rate of Pay</h2>
  <p>The regular rate includes most forms of compensation: hourly wages, non-discretionary bonuses, commissions, and shift differentials. It excludes discretionary bonuses, gifts, and certain other payments. Overtime is calculated on the regular rate, not just base wages.</p>
  <h2>Common Misclassification Traps</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Assistant managers who primarily perform non-managerial tasks</li>
    <li>IT workers classified as "computer professionals" who don't meet the duties test</li>
    <li>"Highly compensated" exemption misapplied to employees earning under $107,432/year</li>
    <li>Inside sales employees misclassified as exempt outside sales</li>
  </ul>
</BaseLayout>
